<Link id="l00234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="234"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Contains data and a 16-bit starting address for the data.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00235" /><CodeLine lineNumber="235"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The byte count specifies number of data bytes in the record.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="236" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a9a50f8bf29974951a166212a08837edb"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a9a50f8bf29974951a166212a08837edb">Data</a> = 0,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="237"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Must occur exactly once per file in the last line of the file.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="238"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The data field is empty (thus byte count is 00) and the address</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="239"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// field is typically 0</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00240" /><CodeLine lineNumber="240" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a8e2df6a62da76caf0639c33b2441dbfd"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a8e2df6a62da76caf0639c33b2441dbfd">EndOfFile</a> = 1,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00241" /><CodeLine lineNumber="241"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The data field contains a 16-bit segment base address (thus byte</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00242" /><CodeLine lineNumber="242"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// count is always 02) compatible with 80x86 real mode addressing.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00243" /><CodeLine lineNumber="243"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The address field (typically 0000) is ignored. The segment address</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00244" /><CodeLine lineNumber="244"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// from the most recent 2 record is multiplied by 16 and added to each</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00245" /><CodeLine lineNumber="245"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// subsequent data record address to form the physical starting address</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00246" /><CodeLine lineNumber="246"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// for the data. This allows addressing up to one megabyte of address</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00247" /><CodeLine lineNumber="247"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// space.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00248" /><CodeLine lineNumber="248" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35aa23fe5b66dcc6cf788ccc5fc8339a208"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35aa23fe5b66dcc6cf788ccc5fc8339a208">SegmentAddr</a> = 2,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00249" /><CodeLine lineNumber="249"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// or 80x86 processors, specifies the initial content of the CS:IP</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00250" /><CodeLine lineNumber="250"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// registers. The address field is 0000, the byte count is always 04,</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00251" /><CodeLine lineNumber="251"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// the first two data bytes are the CS value, the latter two are the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00252" /><CodeLine lineNumber="252"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// IP value.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00253" /><CodeLine lineNumber="253" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a6b5fcdbfab85c3e3f9c8428292bb1435"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a6b5fcdbfab85c3e3f9c8428292bb1435">StartAddr80x86</a> = 3,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00254" /><CodeLine lineNumber="254"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Allows for 32 bit addressing (up to 4GiB). The record&#39;s address field</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00255" /><CodeLine lineNumber="255"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// is ignored (typically 0000) and its byte count is always 2 The two</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00256" /><CodeLine lineNumber="256"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// data bytes (big endian) specify the upper 16 bits of the 32 bit</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00257" /><CodeLine lineNumber="257"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// absolute address for all subsequent type 0 records</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00258" /><CodeLine lineNumber="258" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35ae524d4984e373da1467ced1e805501a0"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35ae524d4984e373da1467ced1e805501a0">ExtendedAddr</a> = 4,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00259" /><CodeLine lineNumber="259"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The address field is 0 (not used) and the byte count is always 4</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00260" /><CodeLine lineNumber="260"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The four data bytes represent a 32-bit address value. In the case of</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00261" /><CodeLine lineNumber="261"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// 80386 and higher CPUs, this address is loaded into the EIP register.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00262" /><CodeLine lineNumber="262" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a1ee44c2ba5272564456032e4cababee2"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/objcopy/elf/ihexrecord/#a0edef690b68eda42710473270d9a0f35a1ee44c2ba5272564456032e4cababee2">StartAddr</a> = 5,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00263" /><CodeLine lineNumber="263"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// We have no other valid types</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00706" /><CodeLine lineNumber="706"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// There are two types of string tables that can exist, dynamic and not dynamic.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00707" /><CodeLine lineNumber="707"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// In the dynamic case the string table is allocated. Changing a dynamic string</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00708" /><CodeLine lineNumber="708"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// table would mean altering virtual addresses and thus the memory image. So</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00709" /><CodeLine lineNumber="709"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// dynamic string tables should not have an interface to modify them or</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00710" /><CodeLine lineNumber="710"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// reconstruct them. This type lets us reconstruct a string table. To avoid</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00711" /><CodeLine lineNumber="711"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// this class being used for dynamic string tables (which has happened) the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00712" /><CodeLine lineNumber="712"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// classof method checks that the particular instance is not allocated. This</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00713" /><CodeLine lineNumber="713"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// then agrees with the makeSection method used to construct most sections.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00867" /><CodeLine lineNumber="867"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00868" /><CodeLine lineNumber="868"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// All relocation sections denote relocations to apply to another section.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00869" /><CodeLine lineNumber="869"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// However, some relocation sections use a dynamic symbol table and others use</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00870" /><CodeLine lineNumber="870"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// a regular symbol table. Because the types of the two symbol tables differ in</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00871" /><CodeLine lineNumber="871"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// our system (because they should behave differently) we can&#39;t uniformly</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00872" /><CodeLine lineNumber="872"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// represent all relocations with the same base class if we expose an interface</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00873" /><CodeLine lineNumber="873"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// that mentions the symbol table type. So we split the two base types into two</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00874" /><CodeLine lineNumber="874"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// different classes, one which handles the section the relocation is applied to</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00875" /><CodeLine lineNumber="875"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// and another which handles the symbol table type. The symbol table type is</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00876" /><CodeLine lineNumber="876"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// taken as a type parameter to the class (see RelocSectionWithSymtabBase).</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00877" /><CodeLine lineNumber="877" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/objcopy/elf/relocationsectionbase"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/objcopy/elf/relocationsectionbase">RelocationSectionBase</a> : </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/objcopy/elf/sectionbase/#aa679879f673113d848d520be5db2cc2a">SectionBase</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00878" /><CodeLine lineNumber="878"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">protected</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="879" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/objcopy/elf/relocationsectionbase/#ab6fd94e8484dacd19eed5accacf577cc"><Highlight kind="normal">  <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/objcopy/elf/sectionbase/#aa679879f673113d848d520be5db2cc2a">SectionBase</a> &#42;<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/objcopy/elf/relocationsectionbase/#ab6fd94e8484dacd19eed5accacf577cc">SecToApplyRel</a> = </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">nullptr</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00880" /><CodeLine lineNumber="880"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01178" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1178"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// It is often the case that the ELF header and the program header table are</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01179" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1179"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// not present in any segment. This could be a problem during file layout,</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01180" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1180"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// because other segments may get assigned an offset where either of the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01181" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1181"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// two should reside, which will effectively corrupt the resulting binary.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01182" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1182"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Other than that we use these segments to track program header offsets</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01183" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1183"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// when they may not follow the ELF header.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
